>Now as for powdercoating. I don't think I want to use an engine case
>that has been heated to 400 degrees for a couple of hours for the
>purpose of being encased in ceramic, which by the way is a great insulator.

Wilson recommends a cure for warped overheated cases damaged by detonation
or run without the cooling fan:
"Sometimes , such excessive heat practically remolds the case so the bores
are
drastically out of line. To save such a case, torque it together and bake at
425 F
( 218 C ) for two hours. Then turn off the oven and let the case cool to
room temperature.
Don't move the case while it's cooling. Once cool, repeat this heat /
cooling cycle.
This will actually reshape the case to where align-boring the main and cam
bearing bores
is possible."

Additionally, welding is a viable repair solution to broken magnesium and
aluminum alloy cases.
Welding, as you know, puts intense heat into the parent material in a
localized area.
This is a considerable topic to discuss.

One further consideration to ponder, powdercoat is not ceramic.

Dave \X/





